  <p>Melbourne winters arrive quickly. One week you're in a t-shirt, the next you're reaching for the heater and realising you haven't thought about it since August. Getting your fireplace or wood heater ready in April or early May — before the cold really sets in — means you're not scrambling for a chimney sweep in June when waitlists blow out and every operator in the city is booked solid.</p>

  <p>Here's exactly what to do, in order, to have your fireplace or wood heater safe, clean and ready for the season.</p>

  <h2>Step 1: Book Your Professional Chimney Clean First</h2>

  <p>Everything else on this list comes after this. The chimney clean is the non-negotiable starting point — it needs to happen before you start using the heater for the season, and ideally before you do any other preparation work, since it can disturb soot and debris inside the firebox.</p>

  <p>Why April or May specifically? Two reasons. First, the pre-winter rush starts in June and most good operators fill up fast — April bookings are straightforward, June bookings mean waiting. Second, if the inspection reveals anything that needs attention — a cracked flue tile, a corroded baffle plate, a damaged seal — you have time to sort it before you actually need the heater. Discovering a problem in July, in the middle of a cold snap, is a much worse position to be in.</p>

  <p>A professional clean covers the full flue from firebox to chimney pot, removes all creosote and soot buildup, clears any nest or debris blockages, and gives you a verbal condition report on anything that needs attention.</p>

