  <h2>Step 2: Clean Out the Firebox</h2>

  <p>After the professional clean, do a basic clean-out of the firebox itself. Remove any old ash that has accumulated from last season — a small amount of ash on the firebox floor is fine (it actually helps insulate the base of the fire), but more than an inch or so should be cleared out.</p>

  <p>Use a metal ash bucket and a fireplace brush and shovel. Never use a household vacuum on fireplace ash — fine ash particles will destroy the motor and filter. Wait at least 48–72 hours after the last fire before removing ash, as embers can remain hot for far longer than expected.</p>

  <p>Check inside the firebox for any obvious cracks in the firebricks or refractory lining. Small hairline cracks are normal from thermal cycling. Large cracks, missing sections, or crumbling firebricks should be repaired before the season starts — a damaged firebox affects efficiency and can be a safety issue in severe cases.</p>

  <h2>Step 3: Check the Damper (If Your System Has One)</h2>

  <p>Open and close the damper fully to make sure it moves freely and seats properly when closed. A damper that sticks, doesn't close fully, or has visible rust or corrosion should be repaired or replaced. An open damper when the heater isn't in use is essentially an open hole in your ceiling — warm air escapes up the chimney constantly, costing you significantly in heating bills through winter.</p>

  <p>If you're not sure your fireplace has a damper or how to operate it, your chimney sweep will check and demonstrate this during the clean.</p>

  <h2>Step 4: Check Seals and Gaskets on Wood Heaters</h2>

  <p>Freestanding wood heaters rely on door gaskets — rope seals around the door — to control airflow into the firebox. A worn or damaged gasket means you can't properly control combustion, which leads to inefficient burning, more creosote, and a heater that's harder to regulate.</p>

  <p>Test the gasket by closing the door on a piece of paper. If you can pull the paper out easily with the door latched, the gasket has lost its seal and needs replacing. Replacement rope gasket and cement is available from fireplace suppliers and is a straightforward DIY job.</p>

  <p>Also check the glass door seal if your heater has a viewing window, and inspect the baffle plate above the firebox — a warped or damaged baffle affects combustion efficiency.</p>

  <h2>Step 5: Sort Your Firewood Now</h2>

  <p>If you're buying firewood for the season, buy it now rather than in June. Demand spikes in June and July, prices often increase, and the better-quality suppliers sell out of well-seasoned stock first.</p>

  <p>Stick to well-seasoned hardwood — red gum, ironbark or box eucalypts are ideal for Melbourne. Avoid pine, unseasoned green wood, or anything that hisses and steams when burning. Wet wood creates significantly more creosote, undoes the work of a fresh clean faster, and produces far less heat per log.</p>

  <p>Store firewood off the ground, under cover, with airflow around it. A dry, seasoned stack is noticeably lighter than green wood and will have visible end-grain cracking if it's properly dried.</p>

  <h2>Step 6: Check Your Carbon Monoxide Detector</h2>

  <p>If you don't have a carbon monoxide detector in the room where your heater or fireplace is located, get one before you start using it this season. CO is colourless and odourless — you can't detect it without a detector. A partial flue blockage or structural issue can allow CO to accumulate to dangerous levels without producing visible smoke or any obvious sign that something is wrong.</p>

  <p>Detectors are inexpensive and available at any hardware store. Test the battery and replace if needed. This applies every year, not just when you're preparing for the first season.</p>

  <h2>Step 7: Do a Test Fire Before You Rely on It</h2>

  <p>Once everything above is done, light a small test fire on a mild day — not in the middle of a cold snap when you actually need the heat. A small, hot fire lets you confirm the draw is good, the heater is performing normally, and there are no issues before you rely on it for serious winter heating.</p>

  <p>Watch for smoke spillage around the door or into the room, unusual smells, poor draw, or any other signs that something isn't right. If all looks good, you're set for winter.</p>

  <h2>Melbourne-Specific Timing</h2>

  <p>Melbourne's cold weather typically sets in properly by late May to early June, with the coldest months being June, July and August. Overnight lows can drop below 5°C from June onwards, and homes in the outer suburbs, Dandenong Ranges, Yarra Valley, Mornington Peninsula and the north-west corridor experience colder conditions than the inner city.</p>

  <p>Target April for your chimney clean and firewood order. Use May to do the checks above. By the time the first genuinely cold night arrives, you'll have a clean, safe, well-stocked setup ready to go — rather than scrambling to book a sweep with a six-week wait while the house is freezing.</p>
